1. Aims  

The SARS-CoV-2 virions (COVID-19 pandemic) – one of the most concerned human’s health crises starting from January 2020 – has hit the world harshly in almost every single field thus leading to a potential great global recession since people all around the world are directed to shut down a large number of community activities. Yet, the current available approaches to prevent the COVIS spread is not strong enough to resume social activities safely due to several reasons. As a consequently, the urgent need of a real-time and cost-advantage detecting COVID-19 system is obvious. Therefore, this project acts as a critical contribution to such an uncertainty and volatile situation of COVID that could help us to resume community activities, flattening the curve global recession.  

To make a tight knit relation to the project’s mission, we will provide advance Application design and Database illustration. To be popular to the community, the application must be designed not only beautifully but also conveniently. Additionaly, processing the huge volume of data real-time with accuracy and sufficiency is one of the most important keys of our project. Therefore, our credo for the backend stuffs should be “real time, real works, real world”.  

Regarding the timeframe, our project is planned to be executed in 4 months where the first two months for building and training AI modeling and the last two months for integration and synchronization of the system as a whole. The overall timeline is planned in accordance with 5 phases of project management as illustrated in Figure y 

 

2. Plan and Progress  

What and how we do it 

Producing biosensor 

  1. Biological receptor: is used to find the concentration of substance. This is the component which has a responsibility to determine the target analyte when the biosensor interacts with these elements. The signals from this receptor can be generated in the form of light, heat and pH. Furthermore, receptors will get the result from the interaction between the person and some element of the receptor and send the signal to transducer as a result for it diagnose based on the research of scientists about covid-19 patient. 

  1. Transducer: is the second component of traditional biosensor, which is responsible for converting the biological signal from biological receptor. This will decide whether the person is suffering from covid-19 or not based on the results of the interaction between receptors and person. 

  1. Producing micro0electronic components 

Building and training AI modelling 

  1. Using research from scientists about the outstanding features of covid-19 patients when compared with normal. Collect these data from normal people and covid-19 patients, which can up to millions of lines of data. 

  1. Select the suitable model and build the algorithm for analyzing and using these algorithms and data for training our AI model. 

  1. Create the large server for our database as we will connect millions of our device in the world into a network to make our AI model become more and more efficient and expand our data for training the AI model 

Application and data structure: 

The data structure of this project is the huge data which can be up to billions line of records. As the result, this database will enlarge day by day, this can be hard for project owners to predict exactly every field and every table in this database. Hence, using non-relational database is an exceptional idea for this project, which can be suitable for scalable system. As covid-19 is the virus which can develop into the new variation with the more powerful than the previous variation, predicting how database look like with this field can be a challenging task. For this project, we just need to build laboratory for scientists to analyze each variation of this virus, then we will try to collect as much data as possible about this variation. And then we will use this data to create interaction with the chemical substances to detect the outstanding features of this variation and use this for training our bio sensor modal. And then recording this information, and analyzing this data

4. Scope and limitation  

4.1 Biosensor development  

Biosensor is referred to a gadget measuring biological or chemical reactions where an analyte in the reaction is generated into the signals [16], [17]. Given such capability, the vast applications of biosensor are observed in healthcare industry including disease monitoring, drug discovery etc. [18], [19]. In particular, a schematic presentation of a typical biosensor is illustrated in the figure below. As can be seen from the demonstration, there are five fundamental components which are the five in-scope features that our project aims to perform. 

 

Figure x: a schematic presentation of biosensor [20] 

 


 

Feature 

Description 

In scope 

Analyte 

A substance that is needing to be detected  

Bioreceptor 

A molecule that has ability to recognize the analyte. Several examples form of bioreceptors include Enzymes, cells, aptamers, deoxyribonucleic acid (DNA) and antibodies [21], [22]. 

In our case, we will use antibodies for detecting the virus. 

Once the interaction of the bioreceptor with the analyte occurs, signal will be generated. This signal can be in various forms such as heat, pH, light, etc.  

In ours system, we will utilize immunosensor in which antibody-antigen interaction is analogous using the correct conformation [26], [27]. 

Electrochemical transducer 

A transducer acts as a converter to transform bio-recognition into measurable signals. The electrical transducer transforms biochemical information depending on enzymatic catalysis reaction [23], [24]. There are various types of electrical transducer [25]:  

  • potentiometric 

  • amperometric  

  • conductometric  

  • voltammetric 

  • polarographic  

  • impedimetric  

  • capacitive 

  • piezoelectric 

In more detail, it can be illustrated as in Figure below 

 

Figure x: Potential electrochemical biosensor platforms for the detection of various pathogenic viruses including COVID-19 [16]. 

Electronics 

This component’s role is to convert analogue into the digital form of signalization 

Display 

This part is for the output signal 

QR code printed on the personal tag component  

This QR code will give a more accessible to data. As being mentioned in previous assignment, the users can use Aole application to scan this QR to read information of other people’s health status. For example, if I would like to know the COVID detecting status of my friend, I will use application to scan this QR code and it will return their 10 latest checking result on my application (The prototype is provided in Figure a below). 

 

Figure a: Prototype of screen result when using Axole application to scan someone’s QR code printed on personal sensor tag. 

Out of sscope 

Detecting the newest variants 

Since the SARS-CoV-2 has been involving quickly with its new variants. The current medical industry capability is not able to project all possible scenario that the new forms if the virus could be. In other words, we are not able to produce the Bioreceptor that interacts with the newest variants but the already-lab-studied ones only. For example, when the Omicron Varian is recognized, it will take weeks for medical lab to conduct research on it. Then, it takes us further couple of weeks to develop new version of sensor.

4.2 AI camera  

 


 

Feature 

Description 

In scope 

Temperature checking (thermographic/ infrared camera) 

Any organism or object has its own amount of heat that is in the form of light human vision cannot see. Therefore, we need a gadget to reflect the temperature in visual capture. Therefore, the infrared radiation camera can be adopted to analyze a human’s temperature which can be used to reflect temperature in real-time [29]. As the following Figure demonstrated, the object’s heat is reflected using IR frequencies. 

 

 

Figure z: The electromagnetic spectrum of infrared radiation [28] 

 

Regarding the purpose of Axole, we desire to measure human’s temperature because fewer is one of the symptoms of infected individuals. Thus, using infrared radiation for measuring the heat is the most optimal approach. However, only thermographic camera is not enough because not all people with fewer are COVID-19 infected. Thus, this results in our innovative product of cough sound checking to detect the virus which will be presented in the following part.  

Cough sound checking 

Mathematical Modelling 

Before the COVID-19 pandemic, there are other Respiratory Voice Diagnostics studied in healthcare industry, including asthma, tuberculosis, bronchitic, which uses acoustic features to detect pathologies. Thus, similar AI product to detect SARS-CoV-2 virus is not infeasible. For instance, Imran et al. [33] employed CNN architectures whose model is pre-trained on general sounds and then fine-tuned on COVID-19 data. However, Axole system will adopt different model since we will exploit nonlinear dynamics with time series Recurrence Quantification Analysis (RQA) to classified to COVID-infected and the healthy individuals, which is similar to the research of Mouawad et al. [34]. In more detail, the steps needed to be done is listed as follows: 

 

Figure x: Framework for symbolic RQA estimation [34] 

1. Transform signal into Mel Frequency Cepstral Coefficients (MFCCs) to recognize the audio signals in various forms.  

2. Using Variable Markov Oracle (VMO) for data symbolization [35] 

3. Recurrence Quantification Analysis:  

  • Computing symbolic RP 

  • Deriving the symbolic RQA 

 

Dataset for AI training  

Parameters: 

  • Audio recordings of coughing 3 times and uttering vowels “ah”, “oh”, “eh” 

  • Age  

  • Gender  

  • Country of residence  

  • Smoking habits  

 

Note: voice attributes include  

  • MFCCs [30] 

  • Vowel formants [31] 

  • Jitter 

  • Shimmer  

  • Mean harmonics-to-noise ratio (HNR) [32] 

Reflecting the COVID status on screen  

The data is visualized on a displayed screen for monitoring purpose by connect camera with a PC or laptop.  

Out of scope 

Send alert to smartphone application 

Since the camera is using AR technologies to scan the crowd and return results on a displayed screen that is connected with the devices. In other words, this is much related to IoT technology adoption rather than 4.0 technology. Thus, connecting with smartphone application requires a lot of effort and expertise for us. Consequently, the project team decided to not implement this feature of AI camera in this project. 

Automatedly alert if there is infected person in the area 

Alerting the crowd of an infected cases would be extremely sensitive and awkward to one individual. Thus, after being discussed comprehensively, Axole decided to not implement such features to the system. 

Clarify cough sound in the crowd 

Although the AI is able to categorize the coughs of whom is COVID-19 infected versus the coughs of whom is not infected, the AI might not be able to detect in the crowd. In other words, if there are too much cacophony, it decreases the ability to function of sound detecting

Feature 

Description

Receiving and storing personal health information 

The application is able to store historical information of the checking whose data is directly extracted from personal sensor tag by sharing via Bluetooth. The data is displayed as demonstrated in the following Figure.  

 

 

QR reader 

Since each sensor is printed QR code on, the application has a feature to scan and read the data from the biosensor personal tag 

Data sharing 

As being mentioned in the earlier part, the application has few features of social media such as add friends, sharing data to your friends. The users can have control over what type of data to share to their friends, what timeframe the data is and who is being shared with.

Once the users exhale to their personal biosensor, and the result is infected case, the application will display Alert and give users detail guideline whom they should contact, where the contact point is, what they should do next. 

 

Additional health indicators 

 

Besides the fundamental information of COVID-19 checking status, other typical health indicators storing on smartphone could also be integrated into Axole app. For example, on iPhone, there is application to store information of height, weight, heart rate, exercise record, blood type, blood pressure, etc. Thus, there will be the optional choice that allows Axole to access to this information to better giving recommendation for the users. 

Since this feature is not the core feature of the Axole system, it is classified as less priority to be implemented.   

Recommendation for users 

Once being integrated with additional health information on smartphone application, Axole app is able to generate advice. For example, if the infected person does not exercise enough, the app will suggest a specific exercise/ yoga activity for the person. Additionally, it will also give general advice of foods needed to supply enough vitamin for the person to fight against virus in their body.

6. Testing  

Testing is essential to measure whether or not the program is functioning correctly and comprehensively. In terms of improvement and development, the results and users' feedbacks will be very valuable to us. There are three components to the testing: performance testing of the biosensor and the AI camera, functional testing, and non-functional testing. The more we delve into the specifics of testing, the more improvements we could make to our application. Furthermore, testing also requires a lot of resources, including time, money, and people. Testing throughout the working process will assist us in shortening the time required for correction and will also make it easier to identify and correct bugs or errors from the very beginning. Thus, we will be able to execute the job following our timetable. The project was successful when it was able to identify COVID-19 positive instances immediately and when the users were able to communicate their health status simultaneously without encountering any issues.  

6.1 Testing Biosensor performance and AI camera 


Steps 

Description 

Statistical hypothesis 

Null hypothesis: our biosensor can detect the SARS-CoV-2 virus and its variants 

Null hypothesis: our AI camera can detect the SARS-CoV-2 virus and its variants 

 

Planning research design 

Expected outcome: drawing out the characteristics of the result performance in biosensor and AI camera (inferences from sample data). 

Measuring variables 

Level of measurement: Categorical (Binary – True/False) 

 

Sampling for statistical analysis  

Probability sampling (random selection to reduce sampling bias) 

Sample size 

100 

Confidence interval  

98% 

Figure x: Data analysis to test our system’s effectiveness 

We will conduct lab test and collect data of its performance. A hundred random participants will be selected for our sample, who will be tested by our system and tested by medical lab. The result of each individual in both tests will be compared where the medical lab is served as a benchmarking to evaluate if our system reflects accurate or not. Then, data will be recorded as ‘True’ or ‘False’. Thus, the data is binary set where ‘True’ reflects a success and ‘Fail’ reflects a failure of detecting the virus. The table above summarizes in step-by step what need to be done to conclude on our hypothesis. In order to conclude the success of our hypothesis, we need to achieve 98% of ‘True’ variables, meaning that we accept only 0.02 error in detecting ability. 

6.1 Testing application  

Functional testing 

  • Unit testing: examining fundamental aspects such as line, code, and method coverage 

  • Smoke testing: examining under what circumstances the code is broken, or failed 

  • Sanity testing: examining critical/important functionalities of the application to ensure its practicability and applicability  

  • Regression Testing: conducting bug fixes after adding new code to ensure the previous block of code still function well 

  • Integration Testing: checking whether the integration of two or more modules work well after being integrated 

  • User Acceptance Testing: Testing of UX/ UI design is highly critical to Axole, regarding business perspective because when the system design does not match expectation of user experience, Axole might not to meet users’ satisfaction, thus leading to our business’s failure. Indeed, several technology businesses could give examples for this type of failure, such as Google Wave, MySpace, Foursquare, etc. according to Oakwood 2017 [14]. Hence, testing of UX, UI design plays a key role in tech start-up that must be tested thoroughly. In more detail, we will conduct A/B testing of minimum viable product (MVP) which is summarized in the Figure below. Essentially, we will create to distinct design of interfaces and compare their performance indicators to see which one is more favorable by the users. In regard to the users’ responses, we will ask 50 random people to give survey feedbacks of their experience on both interfaces and we will select 10 random people to conduct consent interview to get more extensive and insightful feedbacks. Therefore, based on these observations we will design the most intuitive interface. 

  • Localization & Globalization Testing: examining whether the application is working well under cross cultures globally 

  • System Testing: conducting end-to-end testing 

Non-functional testing 

  • Load testing: checking loading ability and responding ability when dealing with huge number of accessing users 

  • Stress testing: given low memory/ hard dish condition (so-called crunch situation) to evaluate the application performance 

  • Recovery testing: given the inputs are not expected or the environment fails to check whether the application is able to recover gracefully 

  • Security testing: checking flaws or vulnerabilities in authentication, access control, and authorization to prevent loss of data or theft 

  • Scalability testing: examining if the application can handle and scale up as the number of users and data volume escalate 

  • Endurance testing: testing the memory leaks

8. Risks 

A variety of risks might occur throughout the project's implementation. Thus, there are four major risks that might have a significant impact on the project, including the following: 

8.1 Time management 

Because of expecting to finish the assignment before the due date of a week, which means everyone will have more time to improve and correct faults in the report and on the websites. To realize this, each member must complete their works on time so that others may assist them if they have any concerns, mistakes to correct, or improvement. 

8.2 Collaboration 

Interpersonal conflicts between members: The fact that our project is centered on technology means that everyone will have a different knowledge of the technological systems involved in the project.  Conflicts may arise amongst members as a result of the fact that everyone has their own opinions about how to express their thoughts. Thus, every member must practice active listening skills to better understand others. Listening before giving opinion and respect others’ ideas are important to avoid this risk. 

Variety of writing styles: Because four people are working on this project, there will be four distinct writing styles on the final report. Readers will be confused as a result of this issue, and certain sections may not be consistent at all points. To prevent this, the team leader will be in charge of checking and wording the report writing to ensure its consistency.  

 

8.3 Technical issue 

First, because not every member is comfortable with working on a website or with HTML or CSS, self-learning or assistance from other members is required to stay up with the project's progress. Second, since the team's members come from backgrounds in IT or business, the team lacks engineering or robotics skills, which also results in a lack of sensor manufacturing expertise. As a result, technical concerns would be resolved via interviews with specialists in the fields of engineering and robotics. Third, our team may not be able to gather all of the cough dataset needed to train AI which exposes to governmental restrictions. 

 

9. Group processes and communication 

In the wake of the COVID-19 epidemic, our project has been transformed into an online activity. Particularly, we utilize Microsoft Teams Group as our primary communication channel throughout the project's execution phase, in addition to the Messenger group chat. We all decided that we would meet on Thursdays from 10 a.m. to 10:30 a.m., once a week. All team members agreed that, in the event that any team member fails to execute their responsibilities in a timely and professional manner, our team would take the following actions:  

  • 1st warning: Allowing them a couple of days to complete their tasks.  

  • 2nd warning: Inquiring as to the reasons why he or she did not complete their job. If they have any questions or encounter any misunderstandings, everyone will do all they can to clarify, assist, and give them the last 24 hours to complete their tasks.  

  • 3rd warning: Marking him/her as procrastination in Peer Assessment Form. Based on his or her demeanor, the leader may decide to report him or her to the lecturer in order to have him or her removed from the team. 

Every meeting has a well-defined aim and expectation, and the agenda has been finalized a week in advance. Besides meeting once a week, the team also communicates progress and questions after each Lecture and Tutorial Session through the primary communication channel. If we are unable to communicate with one another on Microsoft Team, we may all communicate via the Messenger group, which serves as our backup communication method. Aside from that, we make use of Microsoft Teams for storing our shared files and documents.
